Read `AGENT_GUIDE.md` first. It is the shared project contract.

## Cursor priorities
- Treat `global-macro-scanner/` as the real project root
- Prioritize correctness over brevity; keep diffs small and reviewable
- Reuse existing patterns from the codebase before inventing new ones
- For multi-file or structural changes, propose a plan and wait for approval

## Project scope
- Canonical code lives in: `config/`, `data/`, `storage/`, `screener/`, `screening/`, `scheduler/`, `main/`, `scripts/etl/`
- Prefer extending canonical modules over adding ad-hoc scripts
- Treat `backups/` and `*.ib_insync_backup` files as historical artifacts — do not modify
- Avoid touching `data_files/raw/` unless the task explicitly requires it
- For DB work: use `db.py`; do not scatter raw SQL or new `check_*.py` files

## Planning and task docs
- For tasks with 3+ steps or touching multiple files, create or update docs under `docs/tasks/`:
  - `*_plan.md` — scope, phases, and checklist
  - `*_findings.md` — experiments, benchmarks, discoveries
  - `*_progress.md` — what ran, what failed, what is done
- Append to `docs/tasks/global_macro_cleanup_progress.md` for cleanup and structural work
- Keep task docs short and factual; do not create them for trivial edits

## Reuse and anti-bloat
- Before adding new logic, search `config/`, `data/`, `storage/`, `screener/`, `screening/`, `scheduler/`, `main/`, and `scripts/etl/` for existing helpers
- Modify or extend existing functions rather than creating near-duplicate logic elsewhere
- Safe local cleanup only: remove unused imports or dead code in files you are already editing — no cross-directory refactors unless explicitly requested
- Tests should call shared utilities; avoid recreating helper logic inline

## Style
- Pythonic, clear code: small functions, simple loops, minimal classes
- Naming: `snake_case`, descriptive but concise (`get_data`, `load_config`, `run_scan`)
- Imports: absolute where practical, sorted, one-per-line; trim unused imports when touching a file
- Follow the local style in the file being edited (logging, error-handling, typing) rather than introducing a new convention
- No verbose comments or docstrings unless the WHY is non-obvious

## File creation policy
- Default: do not create new `.py` files without justification
- Pre-approved without extra confirmation:
  - Planning, findings, or progress docs under `docs/tasks/`
  - New test files under `tests/` or `scripts/testing/` when tests are explicitly requested
- For any other new file: propose the exact path and purpose first, wait for explicit approval before creating

## Execution safety
- Inspect files before editing; read before writing
- Check `git status --short` before structural moves, cleanup, or multi-file changes
- For any change touching more than one file or ~50 lines: present the plan first, execute only after approval
- After completing an approved step, summarize what changed (files + line ranges) before continuing

## Failure handling
- On any error, unexpected behavior, or missing context: stop immediately
- Report: what failed, why it likely failed, and 1–2 concrete options to fix it
- Do not auto-retry, do not broaden scope to new directories, and do not spawn additional work unless explicitly asked

## Documentation alignment
- Keep docs consistent with `README.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, and `AGENT_GUIDE.md`
- `README.md` is the canonical operator doc — setup, env vars, primary commands live there
- Topic docs under `docs/` defer to `README.md` for setup; they cover specialized detail only
- Do not turn specialized docs into competing READMEs

## Avoid
- Speculative refactors or "nice to have" cleanups outside the stated scope
- New helpers that duplicate existing ones in a different location
- Inventing new entrypoints, CLI flags, or dependency workflows without approval
- Broadening a task on your own when the original request is clear
